<DOC><DOCNO> AP880919-0014 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0051EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Burma-Glance     09-19 0406</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Burma-Glance,0417</SECOND><HEAD>Burma At A Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Burma</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, is a look at Burma, where military commanderSaw Maung overthrew civilian President Maung Maung:   THE LAND _ Burma, on the Bay of Bengal, is nearly the size ofTexas and shares frontiers with Bangladesh, India, China, Thailandand Laos. Resources include fertile soil, teak and other hardwoods,oil and several important minerals. Rangoon, with a population of3.5 million, is the capital and largest city. Mandalay, thesecond-largest city and last capital of the Burmese kings, is ofhistorical and cultural interest. Burma has a tropical monsoonclimate.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE PEOPLE _ About two-thirds of the 38 million people areethnic Burmans, who are related to Tibetans. Important minoritiesinclude Karens, Shans, Chins, Kachins, Chinese and Indian. About 85percent of the people practice Buddhism, with minorities adheringto Islam and Christianity.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE ECONOMY _ Per capita income is about $180 a year, makingBurma one of the world's poorest nations. An agricultural country,Burma once was the world's leading rice exporter but it experiencedfood shortages in 1987. Burma's debt has climbed to more than $3billion.   The black market, fueled by smuggled goods from Thailand andChina, overshadows the official economy.   Burma's economic failure is generally attributed to poorgovernment management and a crippling war against several ethnicminorities seeking autonomy. Japan and West Germany are major aiddonors, and the United States has a modest assistance program,mainly in the anti-drug area.</TEXT><TEXT>   HISTORY _ The Burmese arrived from Tibet before the 9th century,displacing earlier cultures. Burma's golden age was the 12thcentury, when its kings built the spectacular temples of Pagan.Britain ruled it from 1886 to 1948. After a post-independenceexperiment with democracy, a military coup in 1962 brought Gen. NeWin to power. He imposed isolationism and socialized the economy.   Ne Win resigned July 23 after anti-government demonstrations. Hewas replaced by retired Army Gen. Sein Lwin, who resigned Aug. 13after further anti-government riots. Maung Maung, aWestern-educated lawyer, on Aug. 19 became Burma's first civilianpresident since the 1962 coup. Saw Maung, defense minister sinceJuly, ousted Maung Maung in a military coup Sunday.   Burma seeks to maintain a strictly neutralist policy and keepout most foreign influences, including joint ventures with foreigncompanies. It has been nicknamed ``Asia's hermit.'' Tourists areallowed to stay only one week.</TEXT></DOC>